abstract.p:
This paper is concerned with the time-asymptotic stability of a nonlinear wave for the outflow problem of the isentropic compressible Navier–Stokes–Korteweg equations in the half space. Under some suitable assumptions on the spatial-asymptotic states and boundary data, the time-asymptotic profile is a nonlinear wave which is the superposition of a stationary solution and a rarefaction wave. Employing the L2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$L^{2}$$\end{document}-energy method and the decay (in both time and space variables) estimates of each component of the nonlinear wave, we prove that this nonlinear wave is time asymptotically stable under a small initial perturbation.

